<LP>
   Like all companies with "poison pill" provisions, Instron
Corp. hoped that its takeover defense would protect the
company from hostile suitors.
   But now Instron may be getting a taste of its own
medicine.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under the provisions of Instron's pill, stockholders gain
the right to purchase additional shares at below-market
prices whenever an individual or group gains control of 20%
or more of the company's shares. This makes the company more
expensive for a raider to buy.
   But what happens when the existing management group,
rather than a raider, breaks the 20% barrier with no intent
to change the status quo?
   A lawsuit filed earlier this month in a Massachusetts
state court claims it means that the rest of the shareholders
must be granted the lucrative stock-purchase rights
guaranteed by the pill -- even if that outcome turns the
obvious intent of the anti-takeover provision on its head.
   In this case, the lawsuit alleges, Instron's own founders
triggered the poison pill when they declared in a news
release in July that they and family members owned about 39%
of Instron's stock. Ironically, the purpose of the news
release was to oppose a takeover, not to start one.
   While many companies' poison pills explicitly state that
officers and controlling shareholders are exempt from the
pill's provisions, Instron's pill contains no such exemption.
Stephen Carr, a partner at Goodwin, Procter &amp; Hoar, which
drafted the pill, said such a provision wasn't necessary. He
said no "group" of shareholders owns 20% or more and that the
news release didn't create such a group.
   Takeover experts said the lawsuit apparently marks the
first time that controlling shareholders or managers have
been accused of triggering a poison pill.
   "This certainly is a new wrinkle," said Alan Bromberg, a
professor of securities law at Southern Methodist University
in Dallas. Mr. Bromberg said that if the Instron founders in
fact authorized the news release or were acting as a
"controlling group," as defined by the poison pill, the novel
suit might actually succeed.
   Stephen Rabinovitz, a Boston investor, filed the lawsuit
on behalf of himself and other Instron shareholders in
Superior Court in Boston. Mr. Rabinovitz's group had said in
a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission in July
that they were interested in acquiring control of Instron, a
Canton, Mass.-based maker of materials testing instruments.
   Michael Schell, a partner at the New York firm of Skadden,
Arps, Slate, Meagher &amp; Flom who is defending Instron, said
that Mr. Rabinovitz is notorious for "facilitating his own
personal objectives" by "making noise" and filing suits. Mr.
Schell said that Instron intends to vigorously defend against
the suit, although he won't say on what grounds.
   Mr. Schell added that Skadden Arps had no role in writing
the news release or the poison-pill provision.
