   PLANNED PARENTHOOD loses appeal over limits on federal
funds abroad.
   The U.S. appeals court in Manhattan upheld a federal
policy banning the use of U.S. funds to "perform or actively
promote abortions" in foreign countries. The federal aid
involved is family-planning assistance from the Agency for
International Development. The money is distributed to
foreign organizations through Planned Parenthood and other
nongovernmental groups in the U.S.
   Planned Parenthood claimed that the rule, adopted by the
Reagan administration in 1984, violated its free-speech
rights by requiring it to enforce restrictions on speech in
order to qualify for the program. But the Second U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals said no rights were violated because Planned
Parenthood wasn't prohibited from using its own money for the
activities.
   "A policy of not subsidizing the exercise of a fundamental
right differs in an important respect from a prohibition on
the exercise of a fundamental right," the appeals-court panel
said. The ruling upheld a lower-court decision dismissing the
case.
   A Planned Parenthood spokeswoman said the organization is
considering whether to appeal.
