   BAN ON SOME TIMBER SUITS is rejected as unconstitutional.
   The ban was contained in the so-called Northwest Timber
Compromise. Congress enacted the law in 1989 to allow for
limited timber harvests for a year in certain old-growth
forests in California and Oregon that are populated by the
northern spotted owl. The law was designed as a temporary, if
forced, truce between warring environmental and timber
interests while a presidential commission developed a final
plan for protecting the owl, recently designated a threatened
species.
   But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected a
provision of the legislation requiring federal courts to
dismiss suits challenging the timber sales. Reversing a
lower-court ruling, the appeals court said Congress had
violated the constitutional separation of powers by requiring
the courts to rule in a particular way without changing the
underlying laws that would permit such suits.
   The act expires on Sept. 30; Congress has been considering
extending the law for another year because the presidential
panel report itself has been delayed.
   Todd True, an attorney in Seattle for the Sierra Club
Legal Defense Fund, said environmental groups were still
assessing possible suits. He said the ruling would be a
useful precedent in fighting other attempts by Congress to
bar judicial review of environmental laws.
   Mark Rutzick, an attorney in Portland for the Northwest
Forest Resource Council, a timber industry consortium, added,
however: "To tie up a sale, one must prove that it will have
an unlawful impact on the spotted owl." He also said the
timber group is mulling an appeal.
