   FRANCHISEES bring civil racketeering suit against American
Vision.
   In a suit filed in U.S. District Court in New York, eight
franchisees in New York and Georgia allege that American
Vision Centers Inc. profited from store-opening services that
it should have provided at cost and misrepresented the
success of company-owned stores that it sold to franchisees.
The suit also alleges that American Vision claimed
franchisees would make money renewing contact-lens insurance,
then started a division to renew the policies itself.
   The franchisees also claim that American Vision Centers
didn't obtain regulatory approval to sell franchises in New
York state and failed to account for advertising fees --
equal to 6.5% of a franchisee's sales -- that it collected
from franchisees. The suit seeks to recover alleged losses of
more than $1 million, plus treble damages.
   Seth Poppel, American Vision Centers president and chief
operating officer, says the suit is a response to legal and
other actions American Vision Centers has taken against
several of the plaintiffs who allegedly owe his company
money. "The suit is totally without merit," Mr. Poppel says.
"The bulk of our franchisees are profitable and happy." Of
American Vision Centers' 82 stores, 36 are franchisees.
   Mr. Poppel says the failure of numerous franchisees to pay
royalties and other fees has contributed to American Vision
Centers' financial problems.
   The company has reported losses of more than $2.5 million
annually since 1987. During the first half of this year, it
reported further losses of $1.8 million on $18.7 million in
revenue.
