   NEWSPAPER loses bid to keep unpublished photographs
confidential.
   The Albuquerque Journal's pictures were taken of a 1985
highway accident in which 62-year-old Eleanor Barton was
killed. Her husband, John Barton, is suing Ford Motor Co. for
negligence and product liability, alleging that a defect in
her car caused the accident. Both Mr. Barton and Ford sought
the newspaper's unused photos and negatives, saying they were
needed to help determine the relative position of the
vehicles involved in the accident.
   Attorneys for the Albuquerque Journal argued that
producing the pictures interfered with the news process in
violation of the paper's First Amendment rights. But State
District Judge Art Encinias in Santa Fe, N.M., ruled that the
photos are "relevant, essential and material" to deciding key
issues in the case. And the New Mexico Supreme Court refused
without comment the newspaper's request to block the
lower-court order.
   Kent Walz, assistant editor of the Albuquerque Journal,
said the paper planned to comply with the order, but it was
still considering an appeal aimed at clarifying the First
Amendment question.
