   HARVARD LAW SCHOOL reinstates public-interest law
counseling post.
   Harvard Law School Dean Robert C. Clark has appointed
Stacy DeBroff, a lawyer who isn't a member of the faculty, to
the position of public-interest law counselor. Elimination of
the position last year prompted protests from students.
   A Harvard Law School spokesman said "over 100 students"
have already met with Ms. DeBroff. The keen interest in
finding jobs in the public-interest field seems to be an
indication that "there is a new activism among students
here," he said.
   The counseling position was first established in the late
1970s to help students tap the network of increasingly scarce
public-interest jobs.
   Public-interest law includes such areas as legal aid for
the poor, consumer advocacy and congressional staff work, all
paying much less than associate positions at top private law
firms.
